PRINTF(1)                        User Commands                       PRINTF(1)

NAME
       printf - format and print data

SYNOPSIS
       printf FORMAT [ARGUMENT]...
       printf OPTION

DESCRIPTION
       Print ARGUMENT(s) according to FORMAT, similar to the C printf
       function.

OPTIONS
       --help display this help and exit

       --version
              output version information and exit

FORMAT
       FORMAT controls the output.  Interpreted sequences:

       \" \\   double-quote and backslash

       \a     alert (BEL)

       \b     backspace

       \c     produce no further output

       \e     escape

       \f     form feed

       \n     new line

       \r     carriage return

       \t     horizontal tab

       \v     vertical tab

       \NNN   byte with octal value NNN (1 to 3 digits)

       \xHH   byte with hexadecimal value HH (1 to 2 digits)

       \uHHHH Unicode character with hex value HHHH (1 to 4 digits)

       \UHHHHHHHH
              Unicode character with hex value HHHHHHHH (1 to 8 digits)

       %%     a single %

       %b     ARGUMENT as a string with '\' escapes interpreted,
              except that octal escapes use \0NNN form

       %q     ARGUMENT is printed in a format that can be reused as
              shell input, escaping non-printable characters

       %d, %i signed decimal integer

       %u     unsigned decimal integer

       %o     unsigned octal integer

       %x, %X unsigned hexadecimal integer

       %e, %E double number in scientific notation

       %f, %F double number

       %g, %G double number in either %e or %f format

       %c     single character (first character of ARGUMENT)

       %s     string

       Width and precision may be specified as '*' to use the next
       ARGUMENT as the value.

       If there are more ARGUMENTs than format specifiers, the FORMAT
       string is reused until all ARGUMENTs are consumed.  Missing
       ARGUMENTs are treated as 0 (for numbers) or empty string (for
       strings).

NOTES
       Unlike echo, printf does not append a trailing newline unless
       explicitly specified in FORMAT.  The single-quote prefix ('c or
       "c) for character constants yields the numeric value of the
       character.

EXIT STATUS
       0      if OK

       1      if errors occurred

AUTHORS
